{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20150102181757|640683271","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Mike_McIntyre","to":"Mike McIntyre"}],"pages":{"850185":{"pageid":850185,"ns":0,"title":"Mike McIntyre","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2015-01-02T18:18:40Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{for|the American football coach|Mike MacIntyre}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name        = Mike McIntyre\n|image       = Mikemcintyre.jpg\n|state       = [[North Carolina]]\n|district    = {{ushr|North Carolina|7|7th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 1997\n|term_end    = <!-- January 3, 2015 -->\n|predecessor = [[Charlie Rose (congressman)|Charlie Rose]]\n|successor   = [[David Rouzer]] {{small|(Elect)}}\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1956|8|6}}\n|birth_place = [[Lumberton, North Carolina|Lumberton]], [[North Carolina]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = Dee Strickland\n|children    = Joshua<br>Stephen\n|alma_mater  = [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill]]\n|religion    = [[Presbyterianism]]\n}}\n'''Douglas Carmichael \"Mike\" McIntyre II''' (born August 6, 1956) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|NC|7}}, serving since 1997. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and of the [[Blue Dog Coalition]].\n\nThe district is a large, mostly rural district in the southeastern part of the state, including [[Wilmington, North Carolina|Wilmington]], [[Smithfield, North Carolina|Smithfield]], [[Clinton, North Carolina|Clinton]] and [[Kinston, North Carolina|Kinston]]. Following the [[2010 United States census]], [[Lumberton, North Carolina|Lumberton]], McIntyre's hometown, was mostly redistricted to {{ushr|NC|8}}.\n\nOn January 8, 2014, McIntyre announced he will not seek reelection in the 2014 elections.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Susan|title=House retirements fuel shrinking political center|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2014/01/08/house-centrist-shrinking/4374127/|newspaper=USA Today|date=January 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nMcIntyre is a lifelong resident of [[Lumberton, North Carolina|Lumberton]]. His father, the [[optometrist]] Dr. Douglas McIntyre, was a city councilman. Earlier relatives were prominent members of the [[Robeson County]] bar.  After serving as  student body president in high school, he interned for 7th District Congressman [[Charlie Rose (congressman)|Charlie Rose]], whom he would replace upon the latter's retirement in 1997.<ref>Dalesio, Emery P., and Austin Baird, [http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/09/05/2317418/ex-us-rep-charlie-rose-helped.html \"Ex-U.S. Rep. Charlie Rose helped tobacco farmers\"], AP and ''The News & Observer'' respectively; September 5, 2012. Retrieved 2012-09-05.</ref> He attended the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] as a [[Morehead-Cain Scholarship|Morehead Scholar]], where he graduated [[Phi Beta Kappa]] as a political science major in 1978 and received his Juris Doctor in 1981. McIntyre practiced as an attorney until his election to Congress. He also served on a variety of law and economics related councils in eastern North Carolina and was active in community, church, civic, and professional organizations. [http://mcintyre.house.gov/index.php/about-mike/biography]<ref>{{cite web|last=McIntyre|first=Mike|title=Biography|url=http://mcintyre.house.gov/index.php/about-mike/biography|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nMcIntyre is considered the \"most powerful and effective leader,\" political or otherwise, in southeastern North Carolina.<ref name=SN01>Schreiner, Mark, [http://www.starnewsonline.com/article/20020730/LEADERSHIP/207300022?tc=ar \"Top Government Leader: Mike McIntyre\"], ''[[Wilmington Star-News]]'', July 30, 2002. \"A recent survey of nearly 360 community leaders found that Rep. McIntyre is the most powerful and effective leader in the greater Wilmington region. The region's elite not only placed him atop a list of 45 leading government and political leaders, but first among all leaders in the region\", webpage 1; high school, webpage 3; family, webpage 2. Retrieved 2012-09-05.</ref><ref name=\"House Bio\">[http://mcintyre.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=66&Itemid=8 Biography], McIntyre ''house.gov'' webpage. Retrieved 2012-09-05.</ref> He was the co-author of the tobacco buyout bill that became law and has pumped almost\n$4 billion into the North Carolina economy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://mcintyre.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=66&Itemid=8|accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Timing was right for tobacco buyout|url=http://southeastfarmpress.com/timing-was-right-tobacco-buyout|accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==United States House of Representatives==\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry|Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]] (Ranking Member)\n*'''[[Commission on Security and Cooperation in Europe]]'''\n\n===Party leadership===\nMcIntyre is the top ranking member on the Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seapower & Projection Forces|url=http://armedservices.house.gov/index.cfm/seapower-projection-forces|publisher=Armed Services Committee|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus, Task Force and other memberships===\n*Congressional Prayer Caucus (Co-Chairman) \n*Adopt a Country Caucus (Co-Chairman and Co-Founder)\n*Business and Technology Task Force for the Blue Dog Coalition (Chairman)\n*Congressional Caucus on Hellenic Issues\n*Congressional Nanotechnology Caucus\n*Congressional Science and Math Educational Caucus\n*Congressional Task Force on Responsible Fatherhood (Co-Chairman)\n*Congressional Waterways Caucus (Co-Chairman)\n*Faith and Values Task Force of the U.S. House Democratic Caucus (Co-Chairman)\n*Friends of Scotland Caucus (Co-Chairman and Co-Founder)\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n*Special Operations Forces Caucus (Co-Chairman)\n*Sportsmen's Caucus\n*Task Force on Jobs, Economic Development, and Transportation of the Congressional Rural Caucus (Co-Chairman)\n*United States Naval Academy Board Member\n*Youth Sports Caucus (Co-Chairman and Founder)\n*Congressional Arts Caucus\n\n==Political positions==\nMcIntyre is a somewhat conservative Democrat who opposes abortion and gun control.\n\nIn 2008, McIntyre authored the Veterans Outreach Improvement Act.<ref>\"H.R.28\nLatest Title: Veterans Outreach Improvement Act of 2011; Sponsor: Rep McIntyre, Mike [NC-7] (introduced 1/5/2011); Cosponsors (None); Latest Major Action: 2/18/2011 Referred to House subcommittee. Status: Referred to the Subcommittee on Health.\" From http://www.thomas.gov. New search at Library of Congress Thomas website required for confirmation or update of information; 2012-09-05.</ref> The bill, which is designed to increase funding to veterans' programs, was passed by the House unanimously. He has also written legislation to help tobacco farmers receive government subsidies and buyouts. On September 29, 2008 he voted against the $700 billion bank bailout plan <ref>[http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnn/2008/images/09/29/bailout.rollcall.0929.pdf \"Final Vote Results for Roll Call 674\"], ''turner.com/cnn'', 29-Sep-2008. \"HR 3997 Question: On Concurring in Senate Amendment With An Amendment\nBill title: To amend the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 to provide earnings assistance and\ntax relief to members of the uniformed services, volunteer firefighters, and Peace Corps volunteers and for other purposes.\"</ref> He has indicated his opposition to the national Democratic party plans for a health care reform bill<ref>{{cite news|author= Riley, Charles, and Jeff Simon |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/03/16/house.vote.count/index.html |title=Health care foes 11 votes shy of defeating bill |publisher=CNN.com |date=2010-03-16 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref> and in March 2010, McIntyre voted against the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]]. He said: \"After we help jump start our economy, we should again turn our attention to health care reform \u2013 but with a clean slate.\"<ref>[http://mcintyre.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7:mcintyre-says-yes-to-jobs-no-to-proposed-health-care-reform-bill&catid=1:2010-press-releases&Itemid=26 \"McIntyre Says, 'Yes to Jobs, No to Proposed Health Care Reform Bill'\"], press release, McIntyre ''house.gov'' webpage, March 19, 2010.</ref> McIntyre indicated his support for repeal on multiple occasions.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20001420-503544.html | work=CBS News | first=Stephanie | last=Condon | title=Democrat Joins Calls for Health Care Repeal | date=March 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>Saxton, Scott, [http://www.wect.com/Global/story.asp?S=12222706 \"McIntyre supports repeal of health care bill\"], [[WECT-TV]], March 29, 2010.</ref>  In January 2011, McIntyre was one of 3 Democrats to vote with the unified Republican caucus for the repeal of the recent health care reform law.<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll014.xml \"Final Vote Results for Roll Call 14\"], ''clerk.house.gov'', 19-Jan-2011. \"HR 2; Question:  On Passage Bill title: Repealing the Job-Killing Health Care Law Act.\"</ref> In July 2011, McIntyre was one of five Democrats to vote for the Cut, Cap, and Balance Act.<ref>{{cite web|last=Berman|first=Russell|title=Five Blue Dogs join GOP in vote for 'cut, cap and balance' bill|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/172441-five-blue-dogs-join-gop-in-vote-for-cut-cap-and-balance-bill|publisher=''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''|accessdate=21 July 2011|date=19 July 2011}}</ref> In April 2009, he voted against the [[Matthew Shepard and James Byrd, Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act]].<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll223.xml]. Retrieved February 21, 2014.</ref>  McIntyre is one of the strongest Democratic voices in the House of Representatives in support of stronger counter-terrorism and domestic surveillance laws. He voted in support of the 2001 [[Patriot Act]], the Patriot Act re-authorization of 2006, the [[Protect America Act of 2007]], the [[Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act|FISA]] Amendment act of 2008, the Patriot Act Extension of 2011, the FISA Extension of 2012.\n\n==Political campaigns==\nMcIntyre announced for the Democratic primary for the 7th District a few months before his former boss, Rose, retired after 24 years in Congress.  He finished second in a crowded seven-way primary, and won the runoff with 52 percent of the vote.  He then defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[New Hanover County]] Commissioner Bill Caster in the general election, also by 52 percent of the vote.  \n\n===2006===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2006}}\nMcIntyre was elected to his sixth consecutive term, earning 73% of the popular vote and defeating Republican nominee Shirley Davis.\n\n===2008===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2008#District 7}}\nMcIntyre won against Republican nominee Will Breazeale  with 68.84% of the vote.\n\n===2010===\n{{See also|North Carolina's 7th district election 2010}}\nIn 2010, McIntyre faced his first close race since his initial run for the seat, narrowly defeating Republican nominee [[Ilario Pantano]] with 53.7% of the vote even as the GOP took control of Congress as well as both houses of the state legislature.<ref>{{cite web|title=Election 2010 - North Carolina 7th District - Pantano vs. McIntyre|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2010/house/nc/north_carolina_7th_district_pantano_vs_mcintyre-1675.html|publisher=Real Clear Politics|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref> \n\n===2012===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2012#District 7}}\nMcIntyre's district had been trending Republican for some time, but was made even more Republican in redistricting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/issues/57_21/Race-Ratings-GOP-Looks-for-Major-Gains-North-Carolina-208044-1.html|title=Race Ratings: GOP Looks for Major Gains in North Carolina|date=August 8, 2011|accessdate=August 11, 2011|work=[[Roll Call]]|first=Joshua|last=Miller}}</ref>  Notably, part of Wilmington was shifted to the heavily Republican 3rd District, and much of his hometown of Lumberton was drawn into the 8th District.  It also lost its share of Fayetteville.  To make up for the loss in population, the 7th was pushed to the north, absorbing heavily Republican [[Johnston County, North Carolina|Johnston County]].\n\nAfter considering a run for governor, Mcintyre ran for re-election against Republican state senator and Johnston County resident [[David Rouzer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starnewsonline.com/article/20120126/ARTICLES/120129756/1177?p=all&tc=pgall|title=McIntyre, other Democrats consider running for governor|date=January 26, 2012|accessdate=January 28, 2012|work=[[Star-News]]|first=Patrick|last=Gannon}}</ref>\n\nThe election outcome left McIntyre the winner by 654 votes. A recount requested by Rouzer began on November 26, 2012; two days later, Rouzer conceded the race to McIntyre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fayobserver.com/articles/2012/11/20/1219012|title=David Rouzer calls for recount in 7th District congressional race; U.S. Rep. Mike McIntyre won seat by 655 votes|work=[[Fayetteville Observer]]|first=Andrew|last=Barksdale|date=21 November 2012|accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|last=Lederman|first=Josh|title=Last House race brings 2012 election to an end|url=http://www.boston.com/news/politics/2012/11/30/last-house-race-brings-election-end/E5EBBHXlYLyaGVyBUXWwkI/story.html|work=boston.com|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcIntyre lives in [[Lumberton, North Carolina|Lumberton]] with his wife, Dee Strickland McIntyre. They have two sons, Joshua and Stephen.\n\nMcIntyre was named a Sports Ethics Fellow by the Institute for International Sport in 2008. He has a Black Belt in [[Tae Kwan Do]]<ref name=\"House Bio\"/> and was inducted into the Robeson County Sports Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite news|title=Congressman Mike McIntyre Selected for Induction into the Robeson County Sports Hall of Fame|url=http://mcintyre.house.gov/index.php/newsroom/press-releases/667-congressman-mike-mcintyre-selected-for-induction-into-the-robeson-county-sports-hall-of-fame|accessdate=7 October 2013|date=September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[North Carolina Democratic Party]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mike McIntyre}}\n*[http://www.house.gov/mcintyre/ Congressman Mike McIntyre] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.mike-mcintyre.com/ Mike McIntyre for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/North_Carolina/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Mike_McIntyre_%5BD-7%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = m000485 | ballot = Mike_McIntyre | nndb = 727/000039610 | votesmart = 153 | govtrack = 400266 | opencong = 400266 | rollcall = 295 | politifact = mike-mcintyre | fec = H8NC07044 | opensecrets = N00002356 | assets = mike-mcintyre | legistorm = 365/Rep_Douglas_Carmichael_McIntyre.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = NC/Mike_McIntyre.htm | congress = mike-mcintyre/1505 | worldcat = | cspan = 45960 | rose = | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAldrNAP }}\n*[http://www.starnewsonline.com/section/topic0107 Collected news and commentary] at ''[[Star-News]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charlie Rose (congressman)|Charlie Rose]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from North Carolina|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[North Carolina's 7th congressional district]]|years=1997\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Rouzer]]<br>{{small|Elect}}}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim McGovern (U.S. politician)|Jim McGovern]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=94th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bill Pascrell]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NC-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata \n| NAME              =McIntyre, Mike\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     =August 6, 1956\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    =[[Lumberton, North Carolina]]\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\n| PLACE OF DEATH    =\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McIntyre, Mike}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:American Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of